2026-03-30 16:17:30 - Agent_20260330161349 - INFO - [+] Agent signaled completion: Reviewed 9 CodeQL queries covering XStream 1.4.6 deserialization vulnerabilities (CVE-2013-7285). Confirmed 10 true positive findings across the core attack surface:

1. **XStream.java (all fromXML/unmarshal entry points)** - 13 public deserialization entry points with no type filtering
2. **DefaultMapper.realClass()** - Central sink where XML-derived class names flow to Class.forName() without validation
3. **DynamicProxyConverter.unmarshal()** - Reads interface/handler class names from XML to create proxies with arbitrary InvocationHandlers (primary CVE-2013-7285 enabler)
4. **JavaClassConverter.fromString()** - XML text values passed directly to mapper.realClass()/Class.forName()
5. **SerializableConverter.doUnmarshal()** - Loads XML-derived classes and calls readObject() via reflection
6. **AbstractReflectionConverter.instantiateNewInstance()** - Uses XML 'resolves-to' attribute for arbitrary class instantiation
7. **SerializationMethodInvoker.callReadObject()** - Reflective readObject() invocation on XML-derived class instances
8. **BeanProvider.newInstance()** - Instantiates XML-derived classes via JavaBeanConverter
9. **UseAttributeForEnumMapper.createEnumMapper()** - Dynamic class loading flowing to DependencyInjectionFactory instantiation
10. **XStream class (no type filtering)** - Absence of security filtering API (addPermission/denyTypes/allowTypes/setupDefaultSecurity not present in 1.4.6)

The core vulnerability is that XStream 1.4.6 lacks all security filtering APIs introduced in 1.4.7+, allowing the EventHandler+ProcessBuilder gadget chain to execute OS commands with zero prerequisites (JDK built-ins only).
